SUMMARY:Experimental and Behavioural Economics Seminar Series – Diogo Ger
 aldes (University College Dublin) – Closing the Gender Gap in Multilater
 al Negotiations Through Institutional Design
LOCATION:Room 304\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Diogo Geraldes: “Closing the Gender Gap in Multilateral Negot
 iations Through Institutional Design”\nhttps://diogogeraldes.com/\n\nZoo
 m: https://unimelb.zoom.us/j/82654401351?pwd=V6TMN2ZpNRILVKO2Y5za5S7GjfbAG
 G.1&from=addon\n\nGoogle Maps: https://maps.app.goo.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n
 \nABSTRACT:\nExperimental evidence shows that men earn more than women in 
 majoritarian negotiations. Three stylized modes of behavior emerge as pote
 ntial reasons for the gap: Men sort into making opening offers more often\
 , prefer to partner with other men\, and when partnering with each other\,
  their coalitions are more stable compared to mixed-gender ones. We design
  three experimental interventions to investigate the explanatory role each
  channel plays in the emergence of the gap and\, consequently\, test poten
 tial solutions. We find that enabling everyone to simultaneously make an i
 nitial proposal does not close the earnings gap\, if anything\, it weakly 
 grows in magnitude. Hiding gender eliminates bias in coalition partner cho
 ice and alters bargaining dynamics\, thereby equalizing mean earnings. Fin
 ally\, allowing for the option to commit in bargaining closes the gap\, no
 t only because mixed-gender coalitions become more stable\, but also becau
 se women become preferred partners. Our results highlight how the attribut
 es of the negotiation environment interact with gender\, and suggest that 
 the design of bargaining institutions can be leveraged to promote gender e
 quity.
URL:https://unimelb.zoom.us/j/82654401351?pwd=V6TMN2ZpNRILVKO2Y5za5S7GjfbAG
 G.1&from=addon
END:VEVENT
